description:
This MR brings JUnit 5 to KeY, see #1674.

It includes a migration of existing JUnit 3 and JUnit 4 to JUnit 5, despite the backward-compatibility.

**STATE:** Two parameterized JUnit 4 test cases are missing. 

JUnit 5 has several advantages to JUnit4:

* it exploits lambdas for writing more readable tests. 
* `@TestFactory` allows to create a function which returns a sequence of test cases
  ```java
  @TestFactory Stream<DynamicTest> integerLiterals() {
      return input.stream().map( it -> DynamicTest.dynamicTest(it, () -> test(it)));
  }
  ```
* It has also a very simple parameterization with `@ParameterizedTest`:
  ```java
  @ParameterizedTest
  @ValueSource(ints = {1, 3, 5, -3, 15, Integer.MAX_VALUE}) // six numbers
  void isOdd_ShouldReturnTrueForOddNumbers(int number) {
    assertTrue(Numbers.isOdd(number));
  }
  ```

  You can use `@ValueSource`, `@CsvSource`, `@CsvSourceFile`, `@MethodSource`, or `@EnumSource`
   See <https://www.baeldung.com/parameterized-tests-junit-5> for more information.


**`AutoSuite` is not required anymore.**

This MR allows you to write `\dl_XXX` (where `XXX` is a known KeY sort) as the type in model and ghost fields. For example

```
class Test {
  //@ public instance model \dl_int MY_INTEGER = 0;
  //@ public instance ghost \dl_heap A_HEAP;
}
```

JavaDL types are treated as primitive types, and hence heap independent! Also, like every *primitive type* in KeY, each Java DL type requires a default value. In the latest version the default value for a sort is given in documentation comment on the sort itself. For example, the following definitions define the default value for `NatList` as `nil`.

```
\sorts {
    Nat;
    /*!  @defaultValue(nil) */
    NatList;
}
```

The resolution of default values are post-poned to `Recoder2KeYConverter`, because we require valid namespaces. Therefore, if recoder is queried for the default of a `\dl_${TYPE}` it answered with an DL escape `\dl_DEFAULT_VALUE_${TYPE}`. This DL escape is later special treated in the general conversion of `EscapedExpression` from recoder to KeY classes. 


### Smaller Additions

* KeY-files, which are included in the loaded `KeYUserProblemFile`, are now processed before the Java is read and JML is parsed. This allows access to included symbols inside DL escapes in JML.

* Like `Taclet`s, `Sort` also offers a documentation and an origin string. The documentation string is needed to give human readable explanation to the user (often given by an documentary comment inside a KeY-file) and also for useful additional meta-data. The origin string, a composition of url and line number, allows the user to find the source of sorts definitions directly.





 default it is currently defined as `\dl_XXX_atom`. Similar to `\atom` which is the default of `\free`.

